This function checks if the last character of a given string is an alphabetical character and not part of a word. It returns true if it meets the criteria, or false otherwise. The function uses regular expressions to check for spaces in the input string and then determines whether the last character is alphabetic or not.

Here's how you can implement this function:

```php
function checkIfLastCharIsALetter($txt) {
  // Check if the input string contains any spaces
  $spaces = preg_match('/\s/', $txt);

  // If there are no spaces, return false
  if (!$spaces) {
    return false;
  }

  // Get the last character of the string
  $lastChar = substr($txt, -1);

  // Check if the last character is alphabetic (a-z or A-Z)
  $isAlphabetical = ctype_alpha($lastChar);

  return $isAlphabetical;
}
```

This function uses the `preg_match` function to check for spaces in the input string. If there are no spaces, it returns false because there is only one word and therefore cannot be a separate word.

If there are spaces, it gets the last character of the string using the `substr` function and checks if it's alphabetic using the `ctype_alpha` function. This function returns true if the character is in the range A-Z or a-z, or false otherwise.

